### Arguments Against the Economic System of Capitalism

For the political movement that finds fault with the whole messy enterprise of capitalism, one might consult the entry on [Anti-capitalism](/Anti-capitalism). It’s a rather large topic, as you’ll see.

The magnum opus of criticism, the very bedrock of dissent for many, is [Karl Marx](/Karl_Marx)'s monumental three-volume work, [Das Kapital](/Das_Kapital). It’s a dense, sprawling dissection of the capitalist beast, and frankly, a bit much for anyone with a short attention span.

The criticisms leveled against [capitalism](/Capitalism) are as varied as the people who offer them. They range from mild disagreements about its messy outcomes to a complete rejection of its foundational principles. These critiques emerge from a spectrum of political and philosophical landscapes, including the rather uncompromising realms of [anarchist](/Anarchist) thought, the collectivist ideals of [socialism](/Socialist), the moral pronouncements of various [religious](/Religious) doctrines, and even the exclusionary fervor of some [nationalist](/Nationalist) perspectives. The pathways to dismantling this system are also debated: some advocate for a swift, often violent, [revolution](/Revolution), while others prefer the slow, grinding gears of [political reforms](/Reformism). Then there are those who see some utility in capitalism, but wish to shackle it with social controls, usually through the heavy hand of government regulation, as seen in the [social market](/Social_market) philosophy.

Among the most persistent accusations hurled at capitalism are that it is fundamentally [exploitative](/Exploitation_of_labour), leading to the alienation of the individual from their labor and their very self ([Marx's theory of alienation](/Marx%27s_theory_of_alienation)); that it is inherently unstable, prone to catastrophic collapses and crises; that it is unsustainable, burning through resources with reckless abandon; and that it breeds vast chasms of [economic inequality](/Economic_inequality). It’s accused of reducing human beings to mere [commodities](/Commodity_fetishism), of fostering a [plutocracy](/Plutocracy) rather than a true [democracy](/Democracy), and of eroding fundamental [human rights](/Human_rights) and [national sovereignty](/National_sovereignty). Furthermore, it’s seen as a prime motivator for [imperialist](/Imperialist) expansion and the perpetual engine of [war](/Military%E2%80%93industrial_complex), all for the benefit of a select few at the expense of the many. And let’s not forget the environmentalists, the [leftists](/Left-wing_politics), the [degrowthers](/Degrowth), and others who point out its voracious appetite for natural resources, its contribution to [climate change](/Climate_change), the devastating loss of [biodiversity](/Holocene_extinction), the depletion of [topsoil](/Topsoil), the rampant [eutrophication](/Eutrophication) of waterways, and the sheer mountains of [pollution](/Pollution) and waste it generates. It’s quite the rap sheet.

