#### Intellectuals

The architects and critics: [Adam Smith](/Adam_Smith), the progenitor of the "invisible hand" myth. [Jeremy Bentham](/Jeremy_Bentham), with his utilitarian calculus. [Thomas Robert Malthus](/Thomas_Robert_Malthus), who saw population as the ultimate constraint. [Jean-Baptiste Say](/Jean-Baptiste_Say), who believed in the inherent balance of markets. [David Ricardo](/David_Ricardo), who laid out complex theories of rent and value. [James Mill](/James_Mill), a foundational liberal thinker. [Frédéric Bastiat](/Fr%C3%A9d%C3%A9ric_Bastiat), a staunch defender of free markets. [Eugen von Böhm-Bawerk](/Eugen_von_B%C3%B6hm-Bawerk), a key figure in the Austrian School. [Alfred Marshall](/Alfred_Marshall), who refined neoclassical economics. [Vilfredo Pareto](/Vilfredo_Pareto), with his observations on income distribution. [Max Weber](/Max_Weber), who linked capitalism to the Protestant ethic. [Ludwig von Mises](/Ludwig_von_Mises), a titan of Austrian economics. [Joseph Schumpeter](/Joseph_Schumpeter), who celebrated "creative destruction." [Friedrich Hayek](/Friedrich_Hayek), a fierce advocate for free markets and limited government. [Walter Block](/Walter_Block), a contemporary libertarian economist. [Ronald Coase](/Ronald_Coase), known for his work on transaction costs. [George Stigler](/George_Stigler), a Nobel laureate for his work on industrial organization and the history of economic ideas. [Milton Friedman](/Milton_Friedman), a towering figure of monetarism and free-market advocacy. [James M. Buchanan](/James_M._Buchanan), a Nobel laureate for his work on public choice theory. [Murray Rothbard](/Murray_Rothbard), a prominent anarcho-capitalist theorist. [Thomas Sowell](/Thomas_Sowell), a prolific conservative economist. [Gary Becker](/Gary_Becker), a Nobel laureate for his work on applying economic analysis to human behavior. [Arthur Laffer](/Arthur_Laffer), famous for the Laffer curve. [Robert Lucas Jr](/Robert_Lucas_Jr), a Nobel laureate for his work on rational expectations. And [Ayn Rand](/Ayn_Rand), the novelist and philosopher whose Objectivist philosophy championed laissez-faire capitalism. A formidable, if often misguided, pantheon.

